# Pin Dependency Versions

When installing or adding dependencies, always pin exact, fully-qualified semver versions.

- No range specifiers: never use `^`, `~`, `>=`, `*`, `x`, or `latest`.
- Always use the full `MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH` form, never partial versions.
- Prefer the latest stable release that is compatible with the rest of the
  stack. "Latest" means latest *compatible* — check peer dependencies before
  jumping to a brand-new major (e.g. don't pair `eslint@10` with plugins that
  only support `^9`, or `typescript@7` with tooling capped at `<6.1.0`).
- Apply this to both `dependencies` and `devDependencies` in `package.json`.

## Installing

Use the exact-version flag so nothing is written with a range:

```bash
pnpm add -E react@19.2.7
pnpm add -DE typescript@7.0.2
```

## Examples

```json
// ❌ BAD — ranges and partial versions
{
  "dependencies": {
    "react": "^19",
    "next": "16.x",
    "typescript": "latest"
  }
}

// ✅ GOOD — exact, fully-qualified versions
{
  "dependencies": {
    "react": "19.2.7",
    "next": "16.2.10",
    "typescript": "7.0.2"
  }
}
```
